column4: Description
Lots of open space and river access. A beautiful spot in Sacramento.
The Cosumnes River Preserve encompasses and protects thousands of acres of wetlands and adjacent uplands.
Deer Creek Hills' 4,060 acres of rolling grasslands and oak woodland preserves the heritage of working ranches and provides endless opportunities for public recreation.

Discovery Park is where the American River meets the Sacramento River. One of Sacramento County’s best boat launches, recreational boaters get the chance to explore both of Sacramento’s wild and scenic rivers.

The Effie Yeaw Nature Center is an award-winning environmental and cultural education center located within the beautiful American River Parkway in Carmichael, California. The Nature Center is currently operated by the American River Natural History Association.

column3: 9950 Elk Grove Florin Rd, Elk Grove, CA 95624
column4: Elk Grove County Park is where recreation meets high society and culture. For the sports-minded, the park offers softball, baseball and soccer fields, as well as horseshoe and volleyball courts and a swim center.

column3: 8556 Gibson Ranch Park Rd, Elverta, CA 95626
column4: Any day is a good day to experience the Country at Gibson Ranch.  So many things to do - and a great place to have your next event! Gibson Ranch Regional Park is located at 8556 Gibson Ranch Road.

column3: 4111 Old Eagle's Nest Road, Mather, CA 95655
column4: On land previously operated by the Air Force, Mather Regional Park has now become the home to a wide range of activities. Where B-52 bombers once practiced take offs and landings, soaring kites and model airplanes now fill the sky.
The McFarland Ranch near Galt is considered a "Living History" ranch, with a goal of providing people with a glimpse of pioneer life in our area.
Paradise Beach is located near California State University, Sacramento, on a oxbow bend in the river which creates a cove where cautious swimmers and skimmers can play.

column3: 1624 Hood Franklin Rd, Elk Grove, CA 95757
column4: Stone Lake's 18,000 acres of protected land in the southern portion of the county near Elk Grove are one of the few urban refuges in the nation. Grasslands, vernal pools and diverse wildlife and plant life make this a year round destination.

Sherman Island is an internationally known windsurfing area, and is extremely popular with locals and visitors. Surrounded on three sides by the Sacramento River and Mayberry Slough, the river runs wide and slow and the Delta breezes blow fiercely across the tree-lined island.
Sailor Bar is a park with a lot of history and wonderful present day opportunities. Settled by gold-seeking sailors, this park was dredged for gold during the Gold Rush.

column1: Sunrise Recreation Areas, Upper and Lower
column3: S Bridge St, Rancho Cordova, CA 95670
column4: These parks provide recreation and education for thousands of visitors each year. The park is divided into two areas, Upper Sunrise and Lower Sunrise.

William B. Pond recreation area is one of the most well established and popular parks along the river. Physically handicapped anglers can access the large, man-made fishing pond via a specialized fishing pier and ramp.

column1: Mural by Lopan and Ernie Fresh
Mural by Kinetic Ideas AKA Anthony Padilla

column4: This free attraction in Sacramento happens every February. The annual date is always on the first or second Saturday of the month.

Cemeteries are just plain fun. They’re spooky, historic and full of nooks and crannies to explore. The Sacramento Historic City Cemetery is no exception, as it’s lined with gorgeous statues and well-kept gardens
On the Jelly Belly factory tour, you can watch Jelly Belly candies being made. How fun is that?
Every second Saturday of the month, Sacramento art galleries stay open late and invite guests to view their pieces for free.

Sacramento is home to many cycling events and trails, and the American River Bike Trail is one of the most beautiful. Also known as the Jedediah Smith Memorial Trail, it begins at Discovery Park in Old Sacramento and ends at Beal’s Point near Folsom Lake.
